Predictive Modeling of Heart Diseases

Statistical Learning - Midterm

Michelle Hajduk

2024-02-27

Introduction

Cardiovascular diseases, claiming 17.9 million lives annually, including heart disease, remain a leading cause of morbidity and mortality globally. This group includes coronary heart disease, cerebrovascular disease, and rheumatic heart disease, with over 80% of deaths attributed to heart attacks and strokes, one-third occurring prematurely in those under 70. Preventing premature deaths relies on identifying high-risk individuals and ensuring timely treatment through counseling and medications (Organization 2021).

In this study, we aim to develop a predictive model for heart disease based on a dataset containing key clinical features. Therefore we use the Heart Failure Prediciton Dataset from kaggle with 918 observations that occured in Cleveland, Hungarian, Switzerland, Long Beach VA, and Stalog. This comprehensive dataset is the result of combining 5 independent heart datasets, comprising a total of 11 common features.

The dataset heart.csv includes the following 12 variables:

  • Age: Age of the patient in years,
  • Sex: Gender of the patient (M: Male, F: Female),
  • ChestPainType: Type of chest pain (TA: Typical Angina, ATA: Atypical Angina, NAP: Non-Anginal Pain, ASY: Asymptomatic),
  • RestingBP: Resting blood pressure in mm Hg,
  • Cholesterol: Serum cholesterol in mm/dl,
  • FastingBS: Fasting blood sugar (1: if FastingBS > 120 mg/dl, 0: otherwise),
  • RestingECG: Resting electrocardiogram results (Normal: Normal, ST: having ST-T wave abnormality, LVH: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes criteria),
  • MaxHR: Maximum heart rate achieved,
  • ExerciseAngina: Exercise-induced angina (Y: Yes, N: No),
  • Oldpeak: Oldpeak = ST (Numeric value measured in depression),
  • ST_Slope: The slope of the peak exercise ST segment (Up: upsloping, Flat: flat, Down: downsloping),
  • HeartDisease: Output class (0: No Heart Disease, 1: Heart Disease).

The former eleven variables capture diverse aspects relevant to the latter heart disease variable, which describes the response variable.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and Pre-Processing

Before building models, a comprehensive exploration of the data is essential to gain insights into the response variable. Additionally, we must preprocess our training data to establish a robust foundation for model creation.

The first step contains splitting the data into a train and a test dataset. It is crucial to split the data before delving into its details to ensure a realistic representation of the situation, so we also have to prevent inadvertent leakage of testing data during preprocessing and model building. We use the createDataPartition() function to partition the data into distinct sets for training (train_data) and testing (test_data). The data split ratio is set at 80%, allocating 80% to the training set and the remaining 20% to the test set. To ensure reproducibility, we specify a seed, allowing for the consistent reproduction of the same random samples across analyses.

# Split between training and testing sets with createDataPartition() from the caret library
set.seed(999) #Set seed for reproducibility
spl = createDataPartition(data$HeartDisease, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)  # 80% for training

# Create train_data and test_data based on spl
train_data = data[spl,] 
test_data = data[-spl,]

To ensure a comparable distribution of heart disease across our datasets, we performe an analysis of the prevalence of heart disease in each dataset. The comparison reveals that the distribution of heart disease is reasonably consistent across the whole dataset, training set, and testing set. The distribution variations are within an acceptable range. This balance is crucial for the generalizability of our models, as it helps prevent biases that may arise from imbalances in class distribution.

Factorizing

Further on, we need to convert the character variables to factors. This is done by using the mutate_if function, ensuring that categorical variables are appropriately formatted. Additionally, the categorical variable FastingBS underwent conversion into a factor. However, due to its initial numerical nature, this conversion had to be handled separately. Furthermore, for the successful prediction of the Heart Disease class in subsequent modeling, it is crucial to convert this response variable into a factor with explicit levels set as No Heart Disease and Heart Disease. As we can observe in the below string output of train_data, the variables have been successfully converted. The dataset now comprises 5 numerical variables (Age, RestingBP, Cholesterol, MaxHR, and OldPeak) alongside 7 categorical variables (Sex, ChestPainType, FastingBS, RestingECG, ExerciseAngina, ST_Slope, and the target variable, HeartDisease).

# Convert character variables to factors using mutate_if function
train_data <- train_data %>% mutate_if(~is.character(.), ~as.factor(.))

# Convert the variable 'FastingBS' to a factor
train_data$FastingBS <- as.factor(train_data$FastingBS)

# Convert the response variable 'HeartDisease' to a factor
train_data$HeartDisease <- as.factor(train_data$HeartDisease)

# Set explicit levels for the 'HeartDisease' factor
levels(train_data$HeartDisease) <- c("No Heart Disease", "Heart Disease")

Numeric Variables

Now, we want to analyse the distribution of the numerical variables. The goal is to gain insights into the spread and patterns within variables such as Age, RestingBP, Cholesterol, MaxHR, and Oldpeak. Therefore we will use the ggpairs() function from the GGally library. This function generates a grid of scatterplots, density plots, and correlation coefficients, offering a comprehensive visualization of the pairwise interactions.

# Define numerical variables
numeric_variables <- c("Age", "RestingBP", "Cholesterol","MaxHR", "Oldpeak")

# Subset the dataset to include only numeric variables
numeric_data <- train_data[, numeric_variables]

# Create a ggpairs plot from library GGally
ggpairs(numeric_data)

The ggpairs plot shows that the numeric variables exhibit no strong correlations. The correlation coefficients range between -0.379 and 0.254, suggesting mainly weak to moderate linear relationships among these variables. Some outliers can be detected by the scatter plots. In dealing with outliers, the typical approaches involve imputation or omission strategies. However, in the context of medical data, it becomes imperative to consider the unique nature of the information. Medical outliers may signify valid and abnormal health conditions demanding attention.

For instance, in cholesterol levels, where the normal value is less than 120 mm/dl, any value exceeding this threshold signals high cholesterol and warrants attention (Clinic 2022). Similarly, variations in resting blood pressure, with a normal range of 120/80, are indicative of potential high or low blood pressure (Association 2023). Moreover, the normal range for MaxHR is contingent on age. Treating the range of MaxHR as outliers would be inappropriate, given the age variability spanning from 28 to 77 (Disease Control and Prevention 2022). Lastly, interpreting Old Peak, a term denoting ST Depression, is pivotal. A baseline of 0 signifies a healthy heart, while any deviation from this baseline indicates ST depressiona critical sign that the cardiac muscle may not be receiving adequate oxygen, among other factors (Kharel et al. 2020). Therefore, a nuanced understanding of medical data is essential to avoid misinterpretation and ensure the preservation of vital health insights.

Looking at the density plots for each variable, it becomes evident that the variable Cholesterol exhibits a high density at low values. To delve deeper into this, we scrutinize the low values through the following histogram and density plot.

train_data$Cholesterol <- ifelse(train_data$Cholesterol == 0, median(train_data$Cholesterol), train_data$Cholesterol)

Skewness

Upon inspecting the ggpairs density plot, it shows that there is skewness present in the distribution of each variable. To enhance the normality of the data and mitigate skewness, it is essential to assess the degree of skewness in each variable before implementing corrective measures.

# Calculate skewness of numerical variables
skewness_values <- sapply(train_data[, sapply(train_data, is.numeric)], skewness)
print(skewness_values)
        Age   RestingBP Cholesterol       MaxHR     Oldpeak 
-0.18229148  0.06240905  1.80804393 -0.13831994  1.01430824

The result shows high positive skewness for Cholesterol and Oldpeak. To address this, we opt for a logarithmic transformation. For Cholesterol, a straightforward log transformation is applied after adding 1 to avoid the logarithm of zero. However, due to the presence of negative values in Oldpeak, a more nuanced approach involving scaling and shifting is required. This technique involves adjusting the data by shifting its values to make them positive and then applying a logarithmic transformation to reduce skewness.

# Apply logarithmic transformation to Cholesterol
train_data$Cholesterol <- log(train_data$Cholesterol + 1)  # Adding 1 to avoid log(0)

# Shift and scale transformation for Oldpeak
shift_constant <- abs(min(train_data$Oldpeak)) + 1  # Adding 1 for additional positivity
train_data$Oldpeak <- sign(train_data$Oldpeak) * log(abs(train_data$Oldpeak) + shift_constant)

Upon re-evaluating the skewness values, it is apparent that these transformations have successfully reduced the skewness in both variables.

skewness_values_after <- sapply(train_data[, sapply(train_data, is.numeric)], skewness)
print(skewness_values_after)

Logistic regression

First we create a logistic regression model with all predictors included. Logistic regression is a handy statistical tool used for classification, especially when dealing with two possible outcomes. In classification modeling, it helps predict the probability of something falling into a specific group. Unlike linear regression, which deals with continuous predictions, logistic regression focuses on the relationship between factors and the likelihood of an event happening or not. It uses a sigmoid curve to transform input factors into probabilities, making it easier to classify things into different groups (James et al. 2013).

We use the glm() function to build the logistic regression model using the train_data. The model is trained with the binomial family to handle binary classification. Subsequently, we predict probabilities on the test data using the trained model. These predicted probabilities are then converted into factor levels, allowing us to classify instances based on the highest probability. The models performance is evaluated using a confusion matrix, and a summary of the logistic regression model is displayed, providing insights into the estimated coefficients and statistical significance of each variable.

# Set a seed for reproducibility
set.seed(999)

# Build a logistic regression model
glm_model <- glm(HeartDisease ~ .,
                 data=train_data,
                 family = binomial)

# Generate predicted probabilities on the test data
prob.test <- predict(glm_model, newdata = test_data, type = "response")

# Convert predicted probabilities to factor levels
pred.test <- as.factor(levels(test_data$HeartDisease)[max.col(prob.test)])

# Evaluate the model using confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(pred.test, test_data$HeartDisease)

The confusion matrix reveals that the model predicted all instances as No Heart Disease, resulting in a sensitivity of 100% but a specificity of 0%. The accuracy is 42.62%, which is only slightly higher than randomly guessing the prevalent class. However, the models coefficients provide insights into the predictors. For instance, being male, experiencing chest pain types ATA or NAP, having a higher cholesterol level, and exhibiting exercise-induced angina are associated with an increased odds of having heart disease. On the other hand, having a flat ST slope and higher Oldpeak values are associated with a decreased odds of heart disease.

As the next step we try to train the model with caret to get a better result. Employing the glmnet method, the model is trained with 1 repeat of 5-fold cross-validation, aiming to enhance accuracy. Data pre-processing involves centering and scaling. The model, lrFit, undergoes tuning with different alpha and lambda values to optimize performance. Subsequently, we evaluate its predictive capabilities on the test data through a confusion matrix.

# Set a seed for reproducibility
set.seed(999)

# Define control parameters for caret
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", 
                     repeats = 1,
                     number = 5)

# Train the logistic regression model using glmnet method
lrFit <- train(HeartDisease ~ ., 
                method = "glmnet",
                family = "binomial",
                data = train_data,
                preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = seq(0, 2, 0.1), lambda = seq(0, .1, 0.01)),
                metric = "Accuracy",
                trControl = ctrl)

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

In the next step we will build a LDA model which is a statistical method utilized for classification and dimensionality reduction, capable of handling multiple classes. Its goal is to find a linear combination of variables that maximizes the separation between different classes while minimizing the variability within each class. LDA assumes normal distribution of features within classes and equal covariance matrices among classes for optimal performance (Hastie, Tibshirani, and Friedman 2009).

The model is built by using the lda() function, excluding the variables RestingBP and RestingECG based on their observed lack of significance during both EDA and initial model training.

# Set seed for reproducibility

# Make predictions on the test data
lda_predictions <- predict(lda_model, newdata = test_data, type = "prob")

A clear separation along LD1 can be notices, suggesting that the model effectively distinguishes between No Heart Disease and Heart Disease cases.

Despite the separation observed in the LDA plot, the model still faces challenges in accurately predicting No Heart Disease cases, as evident from the high false-positive count (72 cases).

The decision of stepwise LDA to choose only one variable may be due to high correlation between ST_Slope and the other strong predictors, implying that additional variables do not provide much more information. Since ST_Slope is categorical, we can not evaluate correlation directly, so we conduct Chi-squared tests for association with the three most important variables.

variables_to_test <- c("ExerciseAngina", "ChestPainType", "MaxHR")

for (variable in variables_to_test) {
  # Create contingency table
  contingency_table <- table(train_data[, variable], train_data[, variable])
  
  # Perform the Chi-squared test
  chi_square_result <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
  
  # Print the result of the Chi-squared test
  print(chi_square_result)
}

In each Chi-squared test, the null hypothesis assumes independence between the two categorical variables being compared. The alternative hypothesis posits a significant association between them. A p-value below 0.05 indicates that there is enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis, suggesting a meaningful association between the variables. All three variables have p-values below 0.05, indicating strong association. Thus, the LDA model with HeartDisease ~ ST_Slope is for now reasonable, achieving an accuracy of 82.51%.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

This step includes building a QDA model. QDA is a classification technique that extends LDA by relaxing the assumption of equal covariance matrices among classes. While LDA assumes that different classes share a common covariance matrix, QDA allows each class to have its own covariance matrix. This flexibility makes QDA more suitable when the underlying data distributions for different classes have distinct covariances (Hastie, Tibshirani, and Friedman 2009).

The model is built by using the qda() function, also excluding the variables RestingBP and RestingECG. The model is trained on the train_data dataset and used to make predictions on the test_data. The print output of the model shows details about the model including prior probabilities of groups, group means, and coefficients of quadratic discriminants.

Naive-Bayes classification

Now, we build a Naive-Bayes model. Naive-Bayes Classification is a probabilistic machine learning technique based on Bayes Theorem, which describes the probability of an event, given prior knowledge of conditions that might be related to the event. The naive aspect comes from the assumption of independence among features, meaning that the presence or absence of one feature does not affect the presence or absence of another, which simplifies the calculation. In a Naive-Bayes Classifier, the goal is to predict the probability of a particular class label given a set of input features (Wasserman 2013).

For creating the model, the function naiveBayes() is used. The laplace parameter is set to 1 to handle cases where a particular combination of feature values is not present in the training data. Following the model summary is printed, predictions on the test_data are made and the model performance is evaluated by a confusion matrix.

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(999)

# Build naive model
model_naive <- naiveBayes(HeartDisease ~ Age + Sex + ChestPainType +  Cholesterol +  FastingBS + MaxHR + ExerciseAngina + Oldpeak + ST_Slope, data = train_data, laplace = 1)

Errors with training and testing sets

In this analysis, we evaluate the performance of the two best models, LDA and Naive Bayes models, using repeated random sub-sampling. The process involves the following steps:

  • Sampling: Randomly select 80% of the dataset for training, leaving the remaining 20% for testing,
  • Training Models: Build LDA and Naive Bayes models using the selected variables and the training subset,
  • Prediction: Make predictions on the testing subset using both models,
  • Evaluation: Assess the models performance by calculating the testing error for both LDA and Naive Bayes.

The entire process is repeated 100 times to obtain a robust estimate of the testing error. The boxplot visualizes the distribution of testing errors for each model.

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(999)

# Create error output matrix
err.out <- matrix(NA, nrow = 100, ncol = 2)

for (i in 1:100) {
  train <- sample(1:nrow(train_data), nrow(train_data) * 0.8)  # 80% of the sample for training
  n.test <- nrow(train_data) * 0.2
  
  # Train
  lda.class <- lda(HeartDisease ~ ST_Slope, data = train_data[train, ])
  naive.class <- naiveBayes(HeartDisease ~ Age + Sex + ChestPainType +  Cholesterol +  FastingBS + MaxHR + ExerciseAngina + Oldpeak + ST_Slope, data = train_data[train, ])
  
  # Predict
  pred.lda <- predict(lda.class, newdata = train_data[-train, ])$class
  pred.naive <- predict(naive.class, newdata = train_data[-train, ])
  
  # Test
  ConfMat.lda <- confusionMatrix(pred.lda, train_data$HeartDisease[-train])
  err.lda <- 1 - ConfMat.lda$overall["Accuracy"]
  
  ConfMat.naive <- confusionMatrix(pred.naive, train_data$HeartDisease[-train])
  err.naive <- 1 - ConfMat.naive$overall["Accuracy"]
  
  err.out[i, 1] <- err.lda
  err.out[i, 2] <- err.naive
}

boxplot(err.out,col="blue",xlab="", ylab="testing error", names=c("lda", "naive"))

The distribution of errors, as shown in the boxplot, indicates that the LDA model has a higher variability in its testing errors compared to the Naive Bayes model. Although the accuracy of LDA might be slightly better, the higher variability suggests that its performance is less consistent across different samples.

The below calculated mean testing error rates for the LDA and Naive Bayes models are 19.51% and 14.54%, respectively. Despite the slightly higher overall mean error for the LDA model, the Naive Bayes model demonstrates a more consistent and lower average testing error across different samples.

# Calculate mean testing error rates
apply(err.out,2,mean)
[1] 0.1951020 0.1454422

When deciding to choose the Naive Bayes model as final model, despite its slightly lower accuracy, several factors need to be considered. One crucial aspect is the nature of the errors made by each model. In the confusion matrix analysis, it is observed that the Naive Bayes model tends to make more false positive errors, predicting more instances as Heart Disease when they are not. This characteristic might be advantageous in certain scenarios, especially if the consequences of missing a true positive (failing to predict an actual Heart Disease case) are considered more severe than the consequences of having some false positives. Additionally, the fact that the Naive Bayes model has a higher number of wrong predictions with Heart Disease, as opposed to LDA, indicates a certain robustness in its ability to detect cases with Heart Disease. This robustness could be valuable in real-world applications where correctly identifying positive cases is a priority. Finally, the decision to proceed with the Naive Bayes model considers not only accuracy but also the nature of errors and specific application requirements.

Incorporing life impact

In this analysis, we explore the incorporation of life impact into model predictions, specifically focusing on the importance of True Positives in predicting Heart Disease. The table below represents the adjusted impact table reflecting the priority of correctly identifying cases of Heart Disease:

Prediction/Reference No Heart Disease Heart Disease
No Heart Disease 0 0
Heart Disease -1 2

The adjusted impact table assigns values to different outcomes, indicating the importance of correct and incorrect predictions, with a higher emphasis on correctly predicting cases of Heart Disease.

To determine the optimal threshold for giving a Heart Disease prediction, we conducted a hyper-parameter selection analysis. We use the final Naive Bayes classifier trained on various threshold values and evaluate its performance across 50 replicates. The boxplot summarizes the impact of True Positives and False Positives at different thresholds.

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(999)

# Adjusted impact table as a vector reflecting the importance of TP
impact.unit <- c(0, -1, 0, 2)

# Selecting the optimal threshold
impact.i <- matrix(NA, nrow = 50, ncol = 10)

# Loop over different threshold values
j <- 0
for (threshold in seq(0.05, 0.5, 0.05)) {
  j <- j + 1
  cat(j)
  
  # Loop over 50 replicates
  for (i in 1:50) {
    # Partition data into training (40%) and testing sets (60%)
    d <- createDataPartition(train_data$HeartDisease, p = 0.4, list = FALSE)
    
    # Select training sample
    train <- train_data[d,]
    test <- train_data[-d,]  
    
    # Consider the Naive Bayes classifier
    full.model <- naiveBayes(HeartDisease ~ Age + Sex + ChestPainType +  Cholesterol +  FastingBS + MaxHR + ExerciseAngina + Oldpeak + ST_Slope, data = train)
    
    # Class probabilities
    probability <- as.data.frame(predict(full.model, test, type = "raw"))
    
    # Predictions with a given threshold
    HD.pred <- rep("No Heart Disease", nrow(test))
    HD.pred[which(probability[, "Heart Disease"] > threshold)] <- "Heart Disease"
    
    # Confusion Matrix
    CM <- confusionMatrix(factor(HD.pred), test$HeartDisease)$table
    
    # Calculate impact per applicant with adjusted impact unit
    impact.applicant <- sum(impact.unit * CM) / sum(CM)
    impact.i[i, j] <- impact.applicant
  }
}
12345678910
# Summary of impact value of predictions
boxplot(impact.i, main = "Hyper-parameter selection",
        ylab = "Impact",
        xlab = "Threshold", names = seq(0.05, 0.5, 0.05), col = "royalblue2")

Final Prediction

In the final step, we utilize the completed Naive-Bayes Model to make predictions on the dataset, taking into account the selected threshold of 0.2. This threshold determines the classification of instances as either Heart Disease or No Heart Disease. The ensuing evaluation involves a confusion matrix to assess the accuracy of these predictions.

# Set seed for reproducibility

# Set the chosen threshold for predicting Heart Disease
threshold <- 0.2

Heart.pred <- rep("No Heart Disease", nrow(test_data))

Comparing the evaluation of the final model with the threshold to the initial naive Bayes model, we observe an increase of 3 predictions for Heart Disease. This results in two false positives, but importantly, one additional true positive, indicating the ability to detect one more case of heart disease by incorporating the threshold. Despite a slightly lower accuracy, the emphasis on prioritizing heart disease cases is evident, aligning with the intended goal.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this report embarked on the exploration of heart disease prediction using a Naive Bayes classifier. We began by conducting exploratory data analysis and preprocessing to gain insights into the dataset. The subsequent development of various models lead to choose the Naive Bayes model. Despite a slightly lower overall accuracy compared to an alternative LDA model, was justified by considering the specific nature of errors and robustness exhibited by the Naive Bayes approach. The model was further fine-tuned by incorporating the impact of prediction thresholds, aiming to prioritize the importance of correctly identifying true positive cases. The final Naive Bayes model, with an optimized threshold of 0.2, demonstrated promising predictive capabilities, showcasing its potential for effective heart disease prediction.
